<P>THE mind is at fir&s;t an open field without par|titions
or enclo&s;ures. To make it turn to mo&s;t
account, it is very proper to divide and enclo&s;e.
In other words, to &s;ort our ob&s;ervations.</P>
<P>SOME men are called &s;agacious, merely on
account of their avarice: Whereas a child can
clench it's fi&s;t the moment it is born.</P>
<P>IT is a point of prudence when you conver&s;e
