the ju&s;tice is as much dependent on his clerk, for
&s;uperior in&s;ight and implicit guidance, as the blind
fellow on his cur that leads him in a &s;tring.
Add to this, that the offer of a cru&s;t will &s;educe
the conductors of either to drag their ma&s;ters into
a kennel.</P>
<P>To remark the different figure made by dif|ferent
